Module 34 – Framing Procedural Intent 🎯📜

Core Message

If you don’t explain why you’re filing, others will assume — and often, assume badly.

⸻

Lesson Introduction

Explicitly stating your procedural intent prevents misinterpretation and strengthens the record.

⸻

Teaching Block

1. State the Purpose
	•	“This filing is intended to preserve appellate rights…”

2. Anticipate Misreadings
	•	Address possible mischaracterizations in the filing itself.

3. Align With Rules
	•	Show how your intent matches procedural law.

⸻

Real-World Illustration

Framing a supplemental brief as “necessary for factual completeness” preempted accusations of improper new argument.

⸻

Assignment Prompt

Task:
Write one sentence of procedural intent for a supplemental filing.

⸻

Model Answer (Sample)

“This supplemental filing is intended solely to ensure the completeness of the factual record for appellate review.”

⸻

Reflection Summary

State your intent, or they’ll write it for you.

⸻

Visual Pairing

Image Concept:
A target labeled “Intent” hit squarely by an arrow. Caption:
“Aim Your Filing’s Purpose.”
